</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Divide
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	nds&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Cal-Maine has a dividend policy adopted by its Board of Directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to the policy, Cal-Maine pays a dividend to shareholders of its Common Stock and Class A Common Stock on a quarterly basis for each quarter for which the Company reports net income attributable to Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. computed in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in an amount equal to one-third (1/3) of such quarterly income. Dividends are paid to shareholders of record as of the 60th day following the last day of such quarter, except for the fourth fiscal quarter.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the fourth quarter, the Company will pay dividends to shareholders of record on the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	65t
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	h day after the quarter end. Dividends are payable on the 15th day following the record date. Following a quarter for which the Company does not report net income attributable to Cal-Maine Foods, Inc., the Company will not pay a dividend for a subsequent profitable quarter until the Company is profitable on a cumulative basis computed from the date of the last quarter for which a dividend was paid.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#x2019;s loan agreements provide that unless otherwise approved by its lenders, the Company must limit dividends paid in any quarter to not exceed an amount equal to one-third of the previous quarter&#x2019;s consolidated net income, which dividends are allowed to be paid if there are no events of default.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, warrants or rights as of May 28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, 201

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	OVERVIEW
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. (&#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;us,&#x201D; &#x201C;our,&#x201D; or the &#x201C;Company&#x201D;) is primarily engaged in the production, grading, packaging, marketing and distribution of fresh shell eggs. Our fiscal year end is the Saturday nearest to May 31 which was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(52 weeks)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(52 weeks),
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(52 weeks)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	for the most recent three fiscal years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our operations are fully integrated.&nbsp;&nbsp;We hatch chicks, grow and maintain flocks of pullets
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(young female chickens, under 18
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	weeks of age), layers (mature female chickens) and breeders (male
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	female birds used to produce fertile eggs to be hatched for egg production flocks), manufacture feed, and produce, process and distribute shell eggs. We are the largest producer and marketer of shell eggs in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;We market the majority of our shell eggs in the southwestern, southeastern, mid-western, and mid-Atlantic regions of the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;We market our shell eggs through our extensive distribution network to a diverse group of customers, including national and regional grocery store chains, club stores, foodservice distributors, and egg product consumers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our operating results are directly tied to egg prices, which are highly volatile and subject to wide fluctuations, and are outside of our control. For example, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	annual average
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Urner-Barry Southeastern Regional Large E
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	gg Market Price per dozen eggs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, for our fiscal 200
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	-201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	ranged from a low of $0.72 during
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2005 to a high of $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2.97
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	during fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The shell egg industry has traditionally been subject to periods of high profitability followed by periods of significant loss. In the past, during periods of high profitability, shell egg producers tended to increase the number of layers in production with a resulting increase in the supply of shell eggs, which generally caused a drop in shell egg prices until supply and demand returned to balance.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, our financial results from year to year may vary significantly.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Shorter term, retail sales of shell eggs historically have been greatest during the fall and winter months and lowest during the summer months.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our need for working capital generally is highest in the last and first fiscal quarters ending in May and August, respectively, when egg prices are normally at seasonal lows.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Prices for shell eggs fluctuate in response to seasonal factors and a natural increase in shell egg production during the spring and early summer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Shell egg prices tend to increase with the start of the school year and are highest prior to holiday periods, particularly Thanksgiving, Christmas, and Easter.&nbsp;&nbsp;Consequently, we generally experience lower sales and net income in our first and fourth fiscal quarters ending in August and May, respectively. Because of the seasonal and quarterly fluctuations, comparisons of our sales and operating results between different quarters within a single fiscal year are not necessarily meaningful comparisons.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	From
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	April
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	through June
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2015, our industry experienced a significant avian influenza (&#x201C;AI&#x201D;) outbreak, primarily in the upper Midwestern U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on several published industry estimates, we believe approximately 12% of the national flock of laying hens was affected.&nbsp;&nbsp;The affected laying hens were either destroyed by the disease or euthanized.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	During April through June 2015, the supply of laying hens decreased substantially, and then began to recover gradually.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	As of June 1, 2016, the national laying hen flock according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture was approximately 10.2% higher than the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	AI
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	reduced flock from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	June 1, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, but remained 1.6% below the number of layers on June 1, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Egg prices increased significantly during the summer and fall of 2015. The average Urner-Barry Thursday prices for the large market (i.e. generic shell eggs) in the southeastern region for the months of June through November 2015 was $2.32 per dozen, with a peak of $2.97
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	August.&nbsp;&nbsp;Subsequent to November 2015, shell egg prices declined.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our average year to date selling price for shell eggs in fiscal 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	of $1.735
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	up 21.4% compared to fiscal 2015; however,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	average selling price
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	for the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	of $1.152
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	w
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	as
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	down 21.7% compared with the same period last year.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Urner Barry price index hit a decade-low level during our fourth quarter, before recovering a portion of th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	decline in recent weeks.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Accordingly, our net average selling prices for eggs for each of our four quarters in fiscal 2016 was particularly volatile:&nbsp;&nbsp;$2.243, $1.970, $1.568 and $1.152 for our first through fourth quarters of fiscal 2016, respectively, compared to $1.354, $1.379, $1.503 and $1.471 for our first through fourth quarters of fiscal 2015, respectively.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	While retail demand trends for shell eggs have been favorable, there has been demand erosion for egg products and reduced egg exports. Based on USDA reports, the laying flock is expected to increase through the end of calendar 2016, creating more supply and the potential for further price declines.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Egg prices will likely remain volatile and future prices will depend on levels of supply and the recovery of institutional
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	demand for eggs which was adversely impacted as a result of the 2015 shortages caused by AI.&nbsp;&nbsp;There have been no positive tests for AI at any of our locations, and we have significantly increased the biosecurity measures at all of our facilities; however, we cannot be certain our flocks will not be affected
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	by AI or other diseases in the future
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	We are one of the largest producers and marketers of value-added specialty shell eggs in the U.S.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For accounting and tax purposes, we classify
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	nutritionally enhanced, cage-free, organic and brown eggs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	as specialty shell eggs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	. They have been a significant and growing segment of the market in recent years. During our fiscal 2016 an increasing number of large restaurant chains, food service companies and grocery chains, including our largest customers, announced goals to transition to a cage-free egg supply chain by specified future dates. We are working with our customers to achieve smooth progress in meeting their goals, and have been making and expect to continue to make significant investments in new and remodeled facilities to meet this demand, including through our Red River joint venture discussed below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, we produced approximately 7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% of the total number of shell eggs sold by us, with approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% of such shell egg production provided by contract producers. Contract producers utilize their facilities
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	produc
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	e
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shell eggs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	layers owned by us. We own the shell eggs produced under these arrangements. For fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, approximately 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% of the total number of shell eggs sold by us
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	purchased from outside producers for resale.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our cost of production is materially affected by feed costs, which are highly volatile and subject to wide fluctuation.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, feed costs averaged about 6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% of our total farm egg production cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes in market prices for corn and soybean meal, the primary ingredients in the feed we use, result in changes in our cost of goods sold.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For our last five fiscal years, average feed cost per dozen sold ranged from a low of $0.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	41
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	in fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	to a high of $0.54 in fiscal 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cost of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	primary
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	feed ingredients, which are commodities, are subject to factors over which we have little or no control such as volatile price changes caused by weather, size of harvest, transportation and storage costs, demand and the agricultural and energy policies of the U.S. and foreign governments.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The large 2015 crops increased available supplies for corn and soybean meal which favorably impacted our results for fiscal 2016, compared to the same period of fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Increased U.S. acreage for both corn and soybeans in 2016 should provide adequate domestic supplies for both of our primary feed ingredients.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Domestic corn supplies could be particularly robust, although domestic soybean stocks could be negatively impacted by increased exports due to reduced supplies from South America.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	During
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the fourth quarter of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, the Company entered into the Red River Valley Egg Farm, LLC (&#x201C;Red River&#x201D;) joint venture with Rose Acre Farms, Inc.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Construction of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	state of the art shell egg production complex near Bogata, Red River County, Texas
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	is nearing completion.&nbsp;&nbsp;The first flock was placed in November 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	n
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	d we expect the complex to be completely stocked in early calendar 2017
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plans for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	complex provide capacity for approximately 1.8 million cage-free laying hens.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	In
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fiscal 2016 we incurred $34.0 million of construction and startup
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	costs associated with the joint venture.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

<EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<A NAME="FIS_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The following table sets forth, for the

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fiscal

	Our operating results are significantly affected by wholesale shell egg market prices and feed costs, which can fluctuate widely and are outside of our control.&nbsp;&nbsp;The majority of our shell eggs are sold at prices related to the Urner Barry Spot Egg Market Quotations for the southeastern and southcentral regions of the country, or formulas related to our costs of production which include the cost of corn and soybean meal.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table shows our net income, net average shell egg selling price, feed cost per dozen produced, and the average Urner Barry wholesale large shell egg prices in the southeast region, for each of our three most recent fiscal years.&nbsp;

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;MARGIN:0PT 36PT 6PT 0PT;">
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">

<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The shell egg industry has traditionally been subject to periods of high profitability followed by periods of significant loss. The periods of high profitability
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	have often
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	reflect
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	ed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	increased consumer demand relative to supply while the periods of significant loss
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	have often
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	reflect
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	ed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	excess supply for the then prevailing consumer demand.&nbsp;&nbsp;Historically, demand for shell eggs increases in line with overall population growth. As reflected above, our operating results fluctuate with changes in the spot egg market quote and feed costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The net average shell egg selling price is the blended price for all sizes and grades of shell eggs, including non-graded shell egg sales, breaking stock and undergrades.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	our average net selling price increase
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	d
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, reflecting strong demand for shell eggs across our markets, and feed costs decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	each year
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	over the previous year.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	In fiscal 2016, our net average selling price increased over the previous year primarily due to supply constraints during much of our fiscal year resulting from the AI outbreak, and feed costs decreased.&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross profit and n
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	e
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	t income for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	increased significantly compared to th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	e prior year, primarily due to increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	selling prices
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	a decrease in feed costs.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our operating results are significantly affected by wholesale shell egg market prices, which are outside of our control. Small changes in production or demand levels can have a large effect on shell egg prices.&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The table below represents an analysis of our non-specialty and specialty, as well as co-pack specialty, shell egg sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;Following the table is a discussion of the information presented in the table.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	N
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	on-specialty shell eggs include all shell egg sales not specifically identified as specialty or co-pack specialty shell egg sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	market is characterized generally by an inelasticity of demand, and small increases in production or decreases in demand can have a large adverse effect on prices and vice-versa.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, non-specialty shell eggs represented approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	67.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% of our shell
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	egg
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	revenue,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	compared to 69
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>

</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	As discussed above, while egg prices increased substantially after the AI outbreak during the early part of our fiscal 2016, egg prices declined to a decade-low level during our fourth quarter, and were 21.7 percent lower than our average selling price in our fiscal 2015 fourth quarter.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Based on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	USDA reports, the laying flock is expected to increase through the end of calendar 2016, creating more supply and the potential for further price declines.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, our sales for the fourth quarter reflect lower volumes primarily related to the loss of a portion of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	a major customer&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	co-pack business. We expect this change to have a negative impact on our fiscal 2017 dozens sold and revenue although the impact on our margins would be lower.
</FONT>
</P>

	a shortage of supply from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	AI affected locations of other producers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, as the AI outbreak had a disproportionately large impact on suppliers of egg products
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	selling
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	price per pound was $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1.213
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	compared to $0.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	91
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, an increase of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	36.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	COST OF SALES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Cost of sales consists of c
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	osts directly related to producing
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, processing and packing shell eggs, purchases of shell eggs from outside producers, processing and packing of liquid and frozen egg products and other non-egg costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;Farm production costs are those costs incurred at the egg production facility, including feed, facility, hen amortization, and other related farm production costs.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The following table presents the key variables affecting our cost of sales:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

	&#xFEFF;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For the thirteen weeks ended May 28, 2016, compared to the same period of 2015, cost of sales decreased from $293.6 million in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015, to $262.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the current period.&nbsp;&nbsp;This decrease of $31.3 million, or 10.7%, was primarily the result of decreased cost of outside egg purchases from $1.43 per dozen in the fourth quarter of fiscal 2015 to $1.11 in the comparable period of fiscal 2016.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;Feed cost per dozen for the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016 was $0.396, compared to $0.406 for the same quarter of fiscal 2015, a decrease of 2.5%.

	Equity in income of affiliates for fiscal 2016 was $5.0 million compared to $2.7 million for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase of $2.3 million is primarily due to our interest in the Southwest Specialty Egg, LLC joint venture as well as increased income from specialty egg sales and patronage dividends in our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	other
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	unconsolidated
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	specialty egg
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	joint ventures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	INCOME TAXES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For the fiscal year ended May 28, 2016, our pre-tax income was $487.2 million, compared to $246.5 million for fiscal 2015. Income tax expense of $169.2 million was recorded for fiscal 2016 with an effective income tax rate of 34.8%, compared to $84.3 million for fiscal 2015 with an effective income tax rate of 34.3%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Items causing our effective rate to differ from the federal statutory income tax rate of 35% are state income taxes and certain items included in income or loss for financial reporting purposes that are not included in taxable income or loss for income tax purposes, including tax exempt interest income, the domestic manufacturers deduction, and net income or loss attributable to noncontrolling interest.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

	Fiscal Year Ended May 3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	0

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	NET SALES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	In fiscal 2015, approximately 97% of our net sales consisted of shell eggs and approximately 3% was egg products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Net sales for the fiscal year ended May 30, 2015 were $1,576.1 million, an increase of $135.2 million, or 9.4%, from net sales of $1,440.9 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015 total dozens of eggs sold increased and egg selling prices increased as compared to fiscal 2014. In fiscal 2015 total dozens of shell eggs sold were 1,063.1 million, an increase of 49.4 million dozen, or 4.9%, compared to 1,013.7 million sold in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	This increase in volume resulted in an increase in net sales of $67.3 million for fiscal 2015 compared with the prior year.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our average selling price of shell eggs increased from $1.362 per dozen for fiscal 2014 to $1.429 per dozen for fiscal 2015, an increase of $0.067 per dozen, or 4.9%, reflecting strong demand for shell eggs across our markets and a higher percentage of specialty egg sales.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The increase in sales price in fiscal 2015 over 2014 resulted in a corresponding increase in net sales of $71.2 million.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our operating results are significantly affected by wholesale shell egg market prices, which are outside of our control. Small changes in production or demand levels can have a large effect on shell egg prices.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Non-specialty shell eggs include all shell egg sales not specifically identified as specialty or co-pack specialty shell egg sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The non-specialty shell egg market is characterized generally by an inelasticity of demand, and small increases in production or decreases in demand can have a large adverse effect on prices and vice-versa.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015, non-specialty shell eggs represented approximately 69.2% of our shell egg dollar sales, compared to 71.3% for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales of non-specialty shell eggs accounted for approximately 78.1% of our total shell egg dozen volumes in fiscal 2015, compared to 80.1% in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, non-specialty shell eggs represented approximately 68.5% of our shell egg dollar sales, compared to 70.4% for the thirteen-week period ended May 31, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, non-specialty shell eggs accounted for approximately 77.1% of the total shell egg dozen volume, compared to 78.4% for the thirteen-week period ended May 31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Specialty eggs, which include nutritionally enhanced, cage free, organic and brown eggs, continued to make up a larger portion of our total shell egg sales dollars and dozens in fiscal 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 2015, specialty eggs accounted for 27.2% of shell egg dollar sales, compared to 24.3% in fiscal 2014, and 19.8% of shell egg dozens sold in fiscal 2015, compared to 17.2% in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, for fiscal 2015, specialty eggs sold through co-pack arrangements accounted for 2.8% of shell egg dollar sales, compared to 3.8% in fiscal 2014, and 2.0% of shell egg dozens sold in fiscal 2015, compared to 2.7% in fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Specialty egg retail prices are less cyclical than non-specialty shell egg prices and are generally higher due to consumer willingness to pay for the increased benefits from these products.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, specialty shell eggs and specialty shell eggs sold through co-pack arrangements represented approximately 28.2% and 2.6%, of our shell egg dollar sales, compared to 25.2% and 3.9% for the thirteen-week period ended May 31, 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, specialty shell eggs and specialty
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

	Table of Contents

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shell eggs sold through co-pack arrangements accounted for approximately 21.0% and 1.9% of the total shell egg dozen volume, compared to 18.7% and 2.9%&nbsp;&nbsp;for the thirteen-week period ended May 31, 2014, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The shell egg sales classified as &#x201C;Other&#x201D; represent hard cooked eggs, hatching eggs, and/or other egg products, which are included with our shell egg operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Egg products are shell eggs that are broken and sold in liquid, frozen, or dried form.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our egg products are sold through our consolidated subsidiaries American Egg Products, LLC (&#x201C;AEP&#x201D;) and Texas Egg Products, LLC (&#x201C;TEP&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 2015 our egg product sales were $45.4 million, an increase of $3.6 million, or 8.6%, compared to $41.8 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our volume of egg products sold for fiscal 2015 was 51.0 million pounds, an increase of 2.1 million pounds, or 4.3%, compared to 48.9 million pounds for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increases in sales volume and market prices in the current fiscal year were due to increased industry demand for egg products, driven by the quick serve restaurant industry as well as export sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;In fiscal 2015, the price per pound of egg products sold was $0.891 compared to $0.855 for fiscal 2014, an increase of 4.2%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	COST OF SALES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Cost of sales consists of costs directly related to producing, processing and packing shell eggs, purchases of shell eggs from outside producers, processing and packing of liquid and frozen egg products and other non-egg costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;Farm production costs are those costs incurred at the egg production facility, including feed, facility, hen amortization, and other related farm production costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table presents the key variables affecting our cost of sales:
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Cost of sales for the fiscal year ended May 30, 2015 was $1,180.4 million, an increase of $42.3 million, or 3.7%, compared to $1,138.1 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Dozens produced increased and dozens purchased from outside shell egg producers increased for fiscal 2015 while cost of feed ingredients decreased in fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;This fiscal year we produced 75.1% of the eggs sold by us, as compared to 74.0% for the previous year. Feed cost for fiscal 2015 was $0.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	39
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	per dozen, compared to $0.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	93
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	per dozen for the prior fiscal year, a decrease of 10.2%.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The decrease in feed cost per dozen resulted in a decrease in cost of sales of $42.7 million for fiscal 2015 compared with 2014.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Gross profit increased from 21.0% of net sales for fiscal 2014 to 25.1% of net sales for fiscal 2015, primarily as a result of lower feed costs and increased egg selling prices.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

	06

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Selling, general and administrative expenses, which include costs of marketing, distribution, accounting and corporate overhead, were $160.4 million in fiscal 2015, an increase of $3.7 million, or 2.3%, compared to $156.7 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stock compensation expense increased $1.2 million for the current fiscal year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stock compensation expense is dependent on the closing price of the Company&#x2019;s Common Stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;For our stock compensation arrangements classified as equity awards (e.g. restricted stock), we recognized stock compensation expense ratably over the vesting period.&nbsp;&nbsp;For our stock compensation arrangements classified as liability awards, we recognize increases or decreases in the value of such awards as increases or decreases, respectively, to stock compensation expense. For additional information, see Note 11 to&nbsp;&nbsp;Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase in specialty egg expense for fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014 is attributable to a 20.8% increase in specialty shell egg dozens sold resulting in an increase in advertising promotions and franchise expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a percentage of net sales, payroll and overhead is 2.0% for fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Other expenses, which include expenses for repairs, professional fees, and insurance, decreased for fiscal 2015 compared with fiscal 2014 as a result of a 2014 confidential legal settlement and related legal fees as well as decreases in other tax expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;During fiscal 2015 we recognized $239,000 in expense resulting from the increase in fair value of contingent consideration applicable to acquisitions, compared to $4.4 million in fiscal 2014, both of which are reflected in other expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5 &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	to Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a percentage of net sales, delivery expense is 3.0% for fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a percent of net sales, selling, general and administrative expense decreased from 10.9% in fiscal 2014 to 10.2% in fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Selling, general, and administrative expense was $42.8 million for the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, a decrease of $919,000, or 2.1%, compared to $43.8 million for the thirteen-week period ended May 31, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Other expenses for the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015, decreased $2.8 million, or 29.7%, compared to the same period of fiscal 2014, primarily as a result of the previously discussed decrease in expense resulting from the fair value of contingent consideration on our acquisition of Maxim as well as a decrease in other tax expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;This decrease is partially offset by the increase in specialty egg expense for the thirteen-week period ended May 30, 2015 compared to the same period of fiscal 2014 which is attributable to a 19.3% increase specialty shell egg dozens sold resulting in an increase in advertising promotions and franchise expense.&nbsp;

	As a result of the above, our operating income was $235.3 million for fiscal 2015, compared to $146.1 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating income as a percent of net sales for fiscal 2015 was 14.9%, compared to 10.1% for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Total other income (expense) consists of income (expenses) not directly charged to, or related to, operations such as interest expense, royalty income, and patronage income, equity in earnings of affiliates, among other items. Total other income for fiscal 2015 was $11.2 million compared to $15.8 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a percent of net sales, total other income was 0.7% for fiscal 2015, compared to 1.12% for fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Other income, net, decreased from $8.8 million in fiscal 2014 to $2.2 million in fiscal 2015 primarily due to a fiscal 2014 non-taxable, non-cash gain of $4.0 million for the remeasurement of our equity interest in Delta Egg to the fair value in connection with the purchase of our joint venture partner&#x2019;s 50% membership interest on March 1, 2014, as well as a $1.4 million decrease in royalty income related to oil and gas wells located on property we own in Texas.&nbsp;&nbsp;For additional information see Note 2 to Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	For the fiscal year ended May 30, 2015, our pre-tax income was $246.5 million, compared to $161.8 million for fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax expense of $84.3 million was recorded for fiscal 2015 with an effective income tax rate of 34.3%, compared to $52.0 million for fiscal 2014 with an effective income tax rate of 32.1%.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Included in fiscal 2014 income tax expense are items related to the acquisition of Delta Egg, which resulted in a $3.3 million decrease to deferred income tax expense related to the outside basis of our equity investment in Delta Egg, with a corresponding non-recurring, non-cash $1.5 million reduction to income taxes expense on the non-taxable remeasurement gain associated with the acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

	Other items causing our effective rate to differ from the federal statutory income tax rate of 35% are state income taxes and certain items included in income or loss for financial reporting purposes that are not included in taxable income or loss for income tax purposes, including tax exempt interest income, the domestic manufacturers deduction, and net income or loss attributable to noncontrolling interest.
</FONT>

	Improved gross profit margins contributed greatly to our positive cash flow from operations in fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014, as well as fiscal 2014 payment of a $28.0 million legal settlement.&nbsp;&nbsp;As discussed above, our gross profit margins increased in fiscal 2015 primarily as a result of an increase in egg prices and dozens sold and a decrease in feed costs compared to fiscal 2014.&nbsp;

	For fiscal 2015, approximately $146.8 million was provided from the sale of short-term investments, $202.5 million was used
</FONT>

	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	purchase short-term investments and net payments of $2.0 million were received from notes receivable and investments in affiliates.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We used $8.2 million for our investment in Southwest Specialty Egg LLC joint venture.&nbsp;&nbsp;For additional information see Note 3 to Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately $82.3 million was used
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	purchase property, plant and equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Refer to the table of material construction projects presented below for additional information on purchases of property, plant and equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Approximately $48.9 million was used
</FONT>

	to pay

	dividends on common stock and $10.2 million was used for principal payments on long-term debt.&nbsp;&nbsp;The net result of these activities was a decrease in cash of $5.9 million from May 31, 2014.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Certain property, plant, and equipment is pledged as collateral on our notes payable and senior secured notes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Unless otherwise approved by our lenders, we are required by provisions of our loan agreements to (1) maintain minimum levels of working capital (current ratio of not less than 1.25 to 1) and net worth (minimum of $90.0 million tangible net worth, plus 45% of cumulative net income since the fiscal year ended May 28, 2005); (2) limit dividends paid in any given quarter to not exceed an amount equal to one third of the previous quarter&#x2019;s consolidated net income (allowed if no events of default); (3) maintain minimum total funded debt to total capitalization (debt to total tangible capitalization ratio not to exceed 55%); and (4) maintain various cash-flow coverage ratios (1.25 to 1), among other restrictions. At May
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, we were in compliance with the financial covenant requirements of all loan agreements. Under certain of the loan agreements, the lenders have the option to require the prepayment of any outstanding borrowings in the event we undergo a change in control, as defined in the applicable loan agreement. Our debt agreements require Fred R. Adams, Jr., our Founder and Chairman Emeritus, or his family, to maintain ownership of Company shares representing not less than 50% of the outstanding voting power of the Company.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The preparation of financial statements in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting standards requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Actual results could differ from these estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Management suggests our Summary of Significant Accounting Policies, as described in Note 1 of the notes to consolidated financial statements, be read in conjunction with this Management&#x2019;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations. We believe the critical accounting policies that most impact our consolidated financial statements are described below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	INVESTMENTS IN SECURITIES AVAILABLE-FOR-SALE
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our investment securities are accounted for in accordance with ASC 320, &#x201C;Investments-Debt and Equity Securities&#x201D; (&#x201C;ASC 320
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company considers all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	investment securities for which there is a determinable fair market value and no restrictions on the Company's ability to sell within the next
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	12 months as available-for-sale, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	carrie
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	s them
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	at fair value, with unrealized gains and losses reported as a separate component of stockholders' equity. Realized gains and losses are included in other income. The cost basis for realized gains and losses on available-for-sale securities is determined on the specific identification method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	ALLOWANCE FOR DOUBTFUL ACCOUNTS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	In the normal course of business, we extend credit to our customers on a short-term basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although credit risk associated with our customers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	considered minimal, we routinely review our accounts receivable balances and make provisions for probable doubtful accounts. In circumstances where management is aware of a specific customer&#x2019;s inability to meet its financial obligations to us (e.g. bankruptcy filings), a specific reserve is recorded to reduce the receivable to the amount expected to be collected.&nbsp;&nbsp;For all other customers, we recognize reserves for bad debt based on the length of time the receivables are past due, generally 100% for amo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	unts more than 60 days past due.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	INVENTORIES
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Inventories of eggs, feed, supplies and livestock are valued principally at the lower of cost (first-in, first-out method) or market.&nbsp;&nbsp;If market prices for eggs and feed grains move substantially lower, we record adjustments to write-down the carrying values of eggs and feed inventories to fair market value. The cost associated with flock inventories, consisting principally of chick purchases, feed, labor, contractor payments and overhead costs, are accumulated during the growing period of approximately 22 weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;Capitalized flock costs are then amortized over the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	flock&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	productive life
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, generally one to two years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Flock mortality is charged to cost of sales as incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;High mortality from disease or extreme temperatures would result in abnormal write-down
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	s to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	flock inventories.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management continually monitors each flock and attempts to take appropriate actions to minimize the risk of mortality loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	LONG-LIVED ASSETS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Depreciable long-lived assets are primarily comprised of buildings and improvements and machinery and equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation is provided by the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives, which are 15 to 25 years for buildings and improvements and 3 to 12 years for machinery and equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;An increase or decrease in the estimated useful lives would result in changes to depreciation expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;When property and equipment are retired, sold, or otherwise disposed of, the asset&#x2019;s carrying amount and related accumulated depreciation are removed from the accounts and any gain or loss is included in operations. We continually reevaluate the carrying value of our long-lived assets, for events or changes in circumstances which indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable from the estimated future cash flows expected to result from its use and eventual disposition.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the sum of the expected future cash flows (undiscounted and without interest charges) are less than the carrying amount of the asset, an impairment loss is recognized to reduce the carrying value of the long-lived asset to the estimated fair value of the asset.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	INTANGIBLE ASSETS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Included in other intangible assets are separable intangible assets acquired in business acquisitions, which include franchise fees, non-compete agreements and customer relationship intangibles, and are amortized over their estimated useful lives of 3 to 25
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	34
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	years.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The gross cost and accumulated amortization of intangible assets are removed when the recorded amounts
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	are
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fully amortized and the asset is no longer in use.&nbsp;&nbsp;Included in other long-lived assets are loan acquisition costs, which are amortized over the life of the related loan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">

</FONT>

</FONT>

</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Goodwill is evaluated for impairment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	annually
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	by first performing a qualitative assessment to determine whether a quantitative goodwill test is necessary
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	After assessing the totality of events or circumstances, if we determine it is more likely than not that the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount, then we perform additional quantitative tests to determine the magnitude of any impairment.
</FONT>
</P>

	, and 201

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales revenue reported in the accompanying consolidated statements of income is reduced to reflect estimated returns and allowances.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company records an estimated sales allowance for returns and discounts at the time of sale using historical trends based on actual sales returns and sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
</P>
<P>

<A HREF="#CALM-20160528X10K_HTM_TOC">

	Table of Contents

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	SALES INCENTIVES PROVIDED TO CUSTOMERS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company periodically provides incentive offers to its customers to encourage purchases. Such offers include current discount offers (e.g., percentage discounts off current purchases), inducement offers (e.g., offers for future discounts subject to a minimum current purchase), and other similar offers. Current discount offers, when accepted by customers, are treated as a reduction to the sales price of the related transaction, while inducement offers, when accepted by customers, are treated as a reduction to sales price based on estimated future redemption rates. Redemption rates are estimated using the Company&#x2019;s historical experience for similar inducement offers. Current discount and inducement offers are presented as a net amount in &#x2018;&#x2018;Net sales.&#x2019;&#x2019;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	STOCK BASED COMPENSATION
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	We account for share-based compensation in accordance with ASC 718, &#x201C;Compensation-Stock Compensation&#x201D; (&#x201C;ASC 718&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;ASC 718 requires all share-based payments to employees, including grants of employee stock options, restricted stock and performance-based shares to be recognized in the income statement based on their fair values. ASC 718 requires the benefits of tax deductions in excess of recognized compensation cost to be reported as a financing cash flow.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 11: Stock Compensation Plans in the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	N
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	otes to the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	onsolidated
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	F
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	inancial
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	S
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	tatements for more information.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	INCOME TAXES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	We determine our effective tax rate by estimating our permanent differences resulting from differing treatment of items for tax and accounting purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are periodically audited by taxing authorities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any audit adjustments affecting permanent differences could have an impact on our effective tax rate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
