<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Investment in Affiliates
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 36PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On April 9, 2015, the Company entered into the Red River Valley Egg Farm, LLC (&#x201C;Red River&#x201D;) joint venture with Rose Acre Farms, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;The joint venture
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	operates
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	a state of the art shell egg production complex near Bogata, Red River County, Texas.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The plans for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	completed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	complex provide capacity for approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million cage-free laying hens.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;As of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, the Company has contributed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$34.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	fund its
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	share of the construction costs and exp
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	ects
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	to make future contributions of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$7.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 36PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On July 25, 2014, the Company entered into the Southwest Specialty Eggs, LLC (&#x201C;SWS&#x201D;) joint venture with Hickman&#x2019;s Egg Ranch.&nbsp;&nbsp;The SWS joint venture subsequently acquired the Egg-Land&#x2019;s Best
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	franchise for Arizona
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	southern California
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Clark County
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(including Las Vegas)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, Nevada.&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	ompany owns
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	of the SWS joint venture.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">

</FONT>

</FONT>

</FONT>

</FONT>

</FONT>

	million
</FONT>

	million
</FONT>

</FONT>

	May 28, 2016
</FONT>

</FONT>

</FONT>

	Depreciation expense was $

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	41.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million in fiscal years

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:14PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company maintains insurance for both property damage and business interruption relating to catastrophic events, such as fires.&nbsp;&nbsp;Insurance recoveries received for property damage and business interruption in excess of the net book value of damaged assets, clean-up and demolition costs, and post-event costs are recognized as income in the period received or committed when all contingencies associated with the recoveries are resolved. Gains on insurance recoveries related to business interruption are recorded within &#x201C;Cost of sales&#x201D; and any gains or losses related to property damage are recorded within &#x201C;Other income (expense).&#x201D; Insurance recoveries related to business interruption are classified as operating cash flows and recoveries related to property damage are
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;Credit Facilities and Long-Term Debt

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Certain property, plant, and equipment is pledged as collateral on our notes payable and senior secured notes.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Unless otherwise approved by our lenders, we are required by provisions of our loan agreements to (1) maintain minimum levels of working capital (ratio of not less than 1.25 to 1) and net worth (minimum of $90.0 million tangible net worth, plus 45% of cumulative net income); (2) limit dividends paid in any given quarter to not exceed an amount equal to one third of the previous quarter&#x2019;s consolidated net income (allowed if no events of default), (3) maintain minimum total funded debt to total capitalization (debt to total tangible capitalization not to exceed 55%); and (4) maintain various current and cash-flow coverage ratios (1.25 to 1), among other restrictions.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, we were in compliance with the financial covenant requirements of all loan agreements.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Under certain of the loan agreements, the lenders have the option to require the prepayment of any outstanding borrowings in the event we undergo a change in control, as defined in the applicable loan agreement. Our debt agreements require Fred R. Adams, Jr., the Company&#x2019;s Founder and Chairman Emeritus, or his family, to maintain ownership of Company shares representing not less than 50% of the outstanding voting power of the Company.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	We are in compliance with those covenants at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:14PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	10.&nbsp;&nbsp;Employee Benefit Plans
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:14PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:14PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company maintains a medical plan that is qualified under Section 401(a) of the Internal Revenue Code and is not subject to tax under present income tax laws.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plan is funded by contributions from the Company and its employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under its plan, the Company self-insures its portion of medical claims for substantially all full-time employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company uses stop-loss insurance to limit its portion of medical claims to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$225,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	per occurrence.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company's expenses including accruals for incurred but not reported claims were approximately $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	11.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million, $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	9.6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million, and $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	9.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million in fiscal years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2016
</FONT>

	2015

Dividends on the Company&#x2019;s common stock are paid to the Plan in cash.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan acquires the Company&#x2019;s common stock, which is listed on the NASDAQ, by using the dividends and the Company&#x2019;s cash contribution to purchase shares in the public markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Plan sold common stock on the NASDAQ to pay benefits to Plan participants.&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants may make contributions to the Plan up to the maximum allowed by the Internal Revenue Service regulations.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company does not match participant contributions.

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Postretirement Medical Plan
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company maintains an unfunded postretirement medical plan to provide limited health benefits to certain qualified retired employees and officers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Retired non-officers and spouses are eligible for coverage until attainment of Medicare eligibility, at which time coverage ceases.&nbsp;&nbsp;Retired officers and spouses are eligible for lifetime benefits under the plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Officers and their spouses, who retired prior to May 1, 2012, must participate in Medicare Plans A and B.&nbsp;&nbsp;Officers, and their spouses, who retire on or after May 1, 2012 must participate in Medicare Plans A, B, and D.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The plan is accounted for in accordance with ASC 715, &#x201C;Compensation &#x2013; Retirement Benefits&#x201D;,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	whereby
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	an employer recognizes the funded status of a defined benefit postretirement plan as an asset or liability, and recognizes changes in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	funded status in the year the change occurs through comprehensive income.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	this
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	expense is recognized on an accrual basis over the employees&#x2019; approximate period of employment. The liability associated with the plan was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$1.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$1.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 30, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The remaining disclosures associated with ASC 715 are immaterial to the company&#x2019;s financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	11.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stock Compensation Plans
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On July 28, 2005, the Company&#x2019;s Board of Directors approved the Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. Stock Appreciation Rights Plan (the "Rights Plan"). The Rights Plan covers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	,000,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shares of Common Stock of the Company. Stock Appreciation Rights ("SARs") may be granted to any employee or non-employee member of the Board of Directors. Upon exercise of a SAR, the holder will receive cash equal to the difference between the fair market value of a single share of Common Stock at the time of exercise and the strike price which is equal to the fair market value of a single share of Common Stock on the date of the grant. The SARs have a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	ten
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	-year term and vest over
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	five
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	years. On August 17, 2005, the Company issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1,185
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	0
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On October 5, 2012, shareholders approved the Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. 2012 Omnibus Long-Term Incentive Plan (&#x201C;2012 Plan&#x201D;). The purpose of the 2012 Plan is to assist us and our subsidiaries in attracting and retaining selected individuals who, serving as our employees, outside directors and consultants, are expected to contribute to our success and to achieve long-term objectives which will benefit our shareholders through the additional incentives inherent in the awards under the 2012 Plan. The maximum number of shares of common stock that are available for awards under the 2012 Plan is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1,0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	00,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shares issuable from the Company&#x2019;s treasury stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Awards may be granted under the 2012 Plan to any employee, any non-employee member of the Company&#x2019;s Board of Directors, and any consultant who is a natural person and provides services to us or one of our subsidiaries (except for incentive stock options which may be granted only to our employees).
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	contain no other service or performance conditions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock is awarded in the name of the recipient and except for the right of disposal, constitutes issued and outstanding shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock for all corporate purposes during the period of restriction including the right to receive dividends.&nbsp;&nbsp;Compensation expense is a fixed amount based on the grant date closing price and is amortized over the vesting period.&nbsp;
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#CALM-20160528X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:14PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	. Contingencies
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:9PT 0PT 5PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Financial Instruments
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:9PT 0PT 5PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company maintains standby letters of credit (&#x201C;LOC&#x201D;) with a bank totaling
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	$3.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May 28, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;These LOCs are collateralized with cash. The cash that collateralizes the LOCs is included in the line item &#x201C;Other assets&#x201D; in the consolidated balance sheets.&nbsp;&nbsp;The outstanding LOCs are for the benefit of certain insurance companies. None of the LOCs are recorded as a liability on the Consolidated Balance Sheets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:9PT 0PT 5PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Litigation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:9PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company is a defendant in certain legal actions, and intends to vigorously defend its position in these actions. The Company assesses the likelihood of material adverse judgments or outcomes to the extent losses are reasonably estimable.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the assessment of a contingency indicates it is probable that a material loss has been incurred and the amount of the liability can be reasonably estimated, the estimated liability is accrued in the Company&#x2019;s financial statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the assessment indicates a potentially material loss contingency is not probable, but is reasonably possible, or is probable but cannot be estimated, then the nature of the contingent liability, together with an estimate of the range of possible loss if determinable and material, would be disclosed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Egg Antitrust Litigation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Since September 25, 2008, the Company has been named as one of several defendants in numerous antitrust cases involving the United States shell egg industry.&nbsp; In some of these cases, the named plaintiffs allege that they purchased eggs or egg products directly from a defendant and have sued on behalf of themselves and a putative class of others who claim to be similarly situated.&nbsp; In other cases, the named plaintiffs allege that they purchased shell eggs and egg products directly from one or more of the defendants but sue only for their own alleged damages and not on behalf of a putative class.&nbsp; In the remaining cases, the named plaintiffs are individuals or companies who allege that they purchased shell eggs indirectly from one or more of the defendants &#x2013; that is, they purchased from retailers that had previously purchased from defendants or other parties &#x2013; and have sued on behalf of themselves and a putative class of others who claim to be similarly situated.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation consolidated all of the putative class actions (as well as certain other cases in which the Company was not a named defendant) for pretrial proceedings in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania. The Pennsylvania court has organized the putative class actions around two groups (direct purchasers and indirect purchasers) and has named interim lead counsel for the named plaintiffs in each group.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	The Direct Purchaser Putative Class Action
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;The direct purchaser putative class cases were consolidated into In re: Processed Egg Products Antitrust Litigation, No. 2:08-md-02002-GP, in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania.&nbsp; As previously reported, in November 2014, the Court approved the Company&#x2019;s settlement with the direct purchaser plaintiff class and entered final judgment dismissing with prejudice the class members&#x2019; claims against the Company.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	The Indirect Purchaser Putative Class Action
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp; The indirect purchaser putative class cases were consolidated into In re: Processed Egg Products Antitrust Litigation, No. 2:08-md-02002-GP, in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania.&nbsp; On April 20-21, 2015, the Court held an evidentiary hearing on the indirect purchaser plaintiffs&#x2019; motion for class certification. On July 2, 2015, the Company filed and joined several motions for summary judgment that sought either dismissal of the entire case or, in the alternative, dismissal of portions of the case.&nbsp;&nbsp;On July 2, 2015, the indirect purchaser plaintiffs filed motions for summary judgment seeking dismissal of certain affirmative defenses based on statutory immunities from federal and state antitrust laws. The Court heard oral argument on the motions for summary judgment on February 22 and 23, 2016. The Court has not ruled on these motions. On September 18, 2015, the Court denied the indirect purchaser plaintiffs&#x2019; motion for class certification of 21 separate classes seeking damages under the laws of 21 states, holding that the plaintiffs were not able to prove that their purported method for ascertaining class membership was reliable or administratively feasible, that common questions would predominate, or that their proposed class approach would be manageable in a single trial.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to barring any right to pursue a class monetary remedy under state law, the Court also denied indirect purchaser plaintiffs&#x2019; request for certification of an injunctive-relief class under federal law.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, the court allowed the indirect purchaser plaintiffs to renew their motion for class certification seeking a federal injunction.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plaintiffs filed their renewed motion to certify an injunctive-relief class on October 23, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company joined the other defendants in opposing that motion on November 20.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plaintiffs filed their reply memorandum on December 11, 2015. The plaintiffs requested oral argument on their renewed motion for injunctive class
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	58
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage59"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#CALM-20160528X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	certification.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plaintiffs also filed a petition with the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit, asking the court to hear an immediate appeal of the trial court&#x2019;s denial of the motion to certify 21 state-law damages classes.&nbsp;&nbsp;On December 3, 2015, the Third Circuit entered an order staying its consideration of the plaintiffs&#x2019; request for an immediate appeal of the damages-class ruling pending the trial court&#x2019;s resolution of the plaintiffs&#x2019; renewed motion to certify an injunctive-relief class.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	The Non-Class Cases
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	. Six of the cases in which plaintiffs do not seek to certify a class have been consolidated with the putative class actions into In re: Processed Egg Products Antitrust Litigation,&nbsp; No. 2:08-md-02002-GP, in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania.&nbsp; The court granted with prejudice the defendants&#x2019; renewed motion to dismiss the non-class plaintiffs&#x2019; claims for damages arising before September 24, 2004. On July 2, 2015, the Company filed and joined several motions for summary judgment that sought either dismissal of all of the claims in all of these cases or, in the alternative, dismissal of portions of these cases.&nbsp;&nbsp;On July 2, 2015, the non-class plaintiffs filed a motion for summary judgment seeking dismissal of certain affirmative defenses based on statutory immunities from federal antitrust law. The Court heard oral argument on the motions for summary judgment on February 22 and 23, 2016. The Court has not ruled on these motions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	&nbsp;Allegations in Each Case
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	. In all of the cases described above, the plaintiffs allege that the Company and certain other large domestic egg producers conspired to reduce the domestic supply of eggs in a concerted effort to raise the price of eggs to artificially high levels.&nbsp;&nbsp;In each case, plaintiffs allege that all defendants agreed to reduce the domestic supply of eggs by: (a) agreeing to limit production; (b) manipulating egg exports; and (c) implementing industry-wide animal welfare guidelines that reduced the number of hens and eggs.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The named plaintiffs in the remaining indirect purchaser putative class action seek treble damages under the statutes and common-law of various states and injunctive relief under the Sherman Act on behalf of themselves and all other putative class members in the United States. Although plaintiffs allege a class period starting in October, 2006 and running &#x201C;through the present,&#x201D; the Court denied the plaintiffs&#x2019; motion to certify classes seeking damages under the laws of 21 states and denied without prejudice the plaintiffs&#x2019; motion to certify an injunctive-relief class, although the plaintiffs have filed a renewed motion to certify an injunctive-relief class, as discussed above.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Five of the original six non-class cases remain pending against the Company.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The principal plaintiffs in these cases are: The Kroger Co.; Publix Super Markets, Inc.; SUPERVALU, Inc.; Safeway, Inc.; Albertsons LLC; H.E. Butt Grocery Co.; The Great Atlantic &amp; Pacific Tea Company, Inc.; Walgreen Co.; Hy-Vee, Inc.; Kraft Food Global, Inc.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, General Mills, Inc., Nestle USA, Inc., and The Kellogg Company.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	In four of these&nbsp;remaining non-class cases, the plaintiffs seek treble damages and injunctive relief under the Sherman Act.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the fifth remaining non-class case, the plaintiff seeks treble damages and injunctive relief under the Sherman Act and the Ohio antitrust act (known as the Valentine Act).&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Pennsylvania court has entered a series of orders related to case management, discovery, class certification, summary judgment, and scheduling.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Pennsylvania court has not set a trial date for any of the Company&#x2019;s remaining consolidated cases (non-class and indirect purchaser cases).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company intends to continue to defend the remaining cases as vigorously as possible based on defenses which the Company believes are meritorious and provable.&nbsp; While management believes that the likelihood of a material adverse outcome in the overall egg antitrust litigation has been significantly reduced as a result of the settlements and rulings described above, there is still a reasonable possibility of a material adverse outcome in the remaining egg antitrust litigation.&nbsp; At the present time, however, it is not possible to estimate the amount of monetary exposure, if any, to the Company because of these cases.&nbsp; Accordingly, adjustments, if any, which might result from the resolution of these remaining legal matters, have not been reflected in the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#CALM-20160528X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	State of Oklahoma Watershed Pollution Litigation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On June 18, 2005, the State of Oklahoma filed suit, in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Oklahoma, against Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. and Tyson Foods, Inc. and affiliates, Cobb-Vantress, Inc., Cargill, Inc. and its affiliate, George&#x2019;s, Inc. and its affiliate, Peterson Farms, Inc. and Simmons Foods, Inc. The State of Oklahoma claims that through the disposal of chicken litter the defendants have polluted the Illinois River Watershed. This watershed provides water to eastern Oklahoma. The complaint seeks injunctive relief and monetary damages, but the claim for monetary damages has been dismissed by the court. Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. discontinued operations in the watershed. Accordingly, we do not anticipate that Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. will be materially affected by the request for injunctive relief unless the court orders substantial affirmative remediation. Since the litigation began, Cal-Maine Foods, Inc. purchased 100% of the membership interests of Benton County Foods, LLC, which is an ongoing commercial shell egg operation within the Illinois River Watershed. Benton County Foods, LLC is not a defendant in the litigation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The trial in the case began in September 2009 and concluded in February 2010. The case was tried to the court without a jury and the court has not yet issued its ruling.&nbsp;Management believes the risk of material loss related to this matter to be remote.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Florida Civil Investigative Demand
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On November 4, 2008, the Company received an antitrust civil investigative demand from the Attorney General of the State of Florida. The demand seeks production of documents and responses to interrogatories relating to the production and sale of eggs and egg products. The Company is cooperating with this investigation and has, on three occasions, entered into an agreement with the State of Florida tolling the statute of limitations applicable to any supposed claims the State is investigating. No allegations of wrongdoing have been made against the Company in this matter.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Other Matters
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	In addition to the above, the Company is involved in various other claims and litigation incidental to its business. Although the outcome of these matters cannot be determined with certainty, management, upon the advice of counsel, is of the opinion that the final outcome should not have a material effect on the Company&#x2019;s consolidated results of operations or financial position.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	At this time, it is not possible for us to predict the ultimate outcome of the matters set forth above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 22.5PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;TEXT-INDENT: -22.5PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Description of Rights and Privileges of Capital Stock&#x2014;Capital Structure Consists of Common
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Stock and Class A Common
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Stock
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company has two classes of capital stock: Common Stock and Class A Common Stock. Holders of shares of the Company&#x2019;s capital stock vote as a single class on all matters submitted to a vote of the stockholders, with each share of Common Stock entitled to one vote and each share of Class A Common Stock entitled to ten votes. The Common Stock and Class A Common Stock have equal liquidation rights and the same dividend rights.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the case of any stock dividend, holders of Common Stock are entitled to receive the same percentage dividend (payable only in shares of Common Stock) as the holders of Class A Common Stock receive (payable only in shares of Class A Common Stock). Upon liquidation, dissolution, or winding-up of the Company, the holders of Common Stock are entitled to share ratably with the holders of Class A Common Stock in all assets available for distribution after payment in full of creditors. The Class A Common Stock may only be issued to Fred R. Adams, Jr., the Company&#x2019;s Founder and Chairman Emeritus, and members of his immediate family, as defined. In the event any share of Class A Common Stock, by operation of law or otherwise is, or shall be deemed to be owned by any person other than Mr. Adams or a member of his immediate family, the voting power of such stock will be reduced from ten votes per share to one vote per share. Also, shares of Class A Common Stock shall be automatically converted into Common Stock on a share per share basis in the event the beneficial or record ownership of any such share of Class A Common Stock is transferred to any person other than Mr. Adams or a member of his immediate family. Each share of Class A Common Stock is convertible, at the option of its holder, into one share of Common Stock at any time. The holders of Common Stock and Class A Common Stock are not entitled to preemptive or subscription rights. In any merger, consolidation or business combination, the consideration to be received per share by holders of Common Stock must be identical to that received by holders of Class A Common Stock, except that if any such transaction in which shares of Capital Stock are distributed, such shares may differ as to voting rights to the extent that voting rights now differ among the classes of capital stock. No class of capital stock may be combined or subdivided unless the other classes of capital stock are combined or subdivided in the same proportion. No dividend may be declared and paid on Class A Common Stock unless the dividend is payable only to the holders of Class A Common Stock and a dividend
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	is declared and paid to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Common Stock concur
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	rently.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	On July 25, 2014, the Board of Directors approved an amendment to the Company&#x2019;s Amended and Restated Certificate of Incorporation to authorize an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	60,000,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shares of common stock and an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2,400,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	shares of Class A common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The primary purpose of the amendment was to provide a sufficient number of authorized shares in order to effect a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	-for-1 stock split of the Company&#x2019;s common stock and Class A common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendment was approved by the Company&#x2019;s stockholders at the Company&#x2019;s annual meeting on October 3, 2014 and the Board of Directors approved the 2-for-1 stock split on the same day.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new shares were distributed on October 31, 2014 to shareholders of record at the close of business on October 17, 2014.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Unless otherwise noted, all prior period share and per share information contained in this report was adjusted to reflect the effect of the stock split.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 22.5PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;TEXT-INDENT: -22.5PT;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value Measures
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company is required to categorize both financial and nonfinancial assets and liabilities based on the following fair value hierarchy.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair value of an asset is the price at which the asset could be sold in an orderly transaction between unrelated, knowledgeable, and willing parties able to engage in the transaction. A liability&#x2019;s fair value is defined as the amount that would be paid to transfer the liability to a new obligor in a transaction between such parties, not the amount that would be paid to settle the liability with the creditor.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 18.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:8PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;WIDTH:0PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Level 1 - Quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 18.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:8PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;WIDTH:0PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Level 2 - Inputs other than quoted prices included in Level 1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:54PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 18.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:8PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;WIDTH:0PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 6PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Level 3 - Unobservable inputs for the asset or liability supported by little or no market activity and are significant to the fair value of the assets or liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The disclosure of fair value of certain financial assets and liabilities recorded at cost are as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6.95PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Cash and cash equivalents
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, accounts receivable, and accounts payable
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The carrying amount approximates fair value due to the short maturity of these instruments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Long-term debt:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The carrying value of the Company&#x2019;s long-term debt is at its stated value. We have not elected to carry our long-term debt at fair value.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	F
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	air values for debt are based on quoted market prices or published forward interest rate curves
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, which are level 2 inputs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	. Estimated fair values are management&#x2019;s estimates
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, which is a level 3 input
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	; however, when there is no readily available market data, the estimated fair values may not represent the amounts that could be realized in a current transaction, and the fair values could change significantly.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	fair value of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	debt i
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	s sensitive to changes in the general level of U.S. interest rates.&nbsp; The Company maintains
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	of its debt as fixed rate in nature to mitigate the impact of fluctuations in interest rates.&nbsp; Under its current policies, the Company does not use interest rate derivative instruments to manage its exposure to interest rate changes.&nbsp; A one percent (1%) adverse move (i.e. decrease) in interest rates would adversely affect the net fair value of the Company&#x2019;s debt by $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	300,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	at May
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The fair value and carrying value of the Company&#x2019;s long-term debt were as follows (in thousands):
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our investment securities &#x2013; available-for-sale classified as level 2 consist of certificates of deposit, time deposits, U
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	S
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	government
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and agency
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	obligations, taxable
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	tax exempt municipal bonds, zero coupon municipal bonds,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	asset-backed securities, foreign government obligations,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	and corporate bonds with maturities of three months or longer when purchased. We classified these securities as current, because amounts invested are available for current operations. Observable inputs for these securities are yields, credit risks, default rates, and volatility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #FFFFFF;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The Company applies fair value accounting guidance to measure non-financial assets and liabilities associated with business acquisitions. These assets and liabilities are measured at fair value for the initial purchase price allocation and are subject to recurring revaluations. The fair value of non-financial assets acquired is determined internally.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our internal valuation methodology for non-financial assets takes into account the remaining estimated life of the assets acquired and what management believes is the market value for those assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Liabilities for contingent consideration (earn-outs) take into account commodity prices based on published
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	forward commodity price curves, projected future egg prices as of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	date of the estimate, and projected future cash flows expected to be received as a result of business acquisition

<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	ITEM 9A.&nbsp;&nbsp;CONTROLS AND
</FONT>
<A NAME="CALM-20160528X10K_HTM_ITEM9ACONTROLS">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:11PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	PROCEDURES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Disclosure Controls and Procedures
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:27PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our disclosure controls and procedures are designed to provide reasonable assurance that information required to be disclosed by us in the reports we file or submit under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#x201C;Exchange Act&#x201D;) is recorded, processed, summarized and reported, within the time periods specified in the Securities and Exchange Commission&#x2019;s rules and forms.&nbsp;&nbsp;Disclosure controls and procedures include, without limitation, controls and procedures designed to ensure that information required to be disclosed by us in the reports that we file or submit under the Exchange Act is accumulated and communicated to management, including our principal executive and principal financial officers, or persons performing similar functions, as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure. Based on an evaluation of our disclosure controls and procedures conducted by our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, together with other financial officers, such officers concluded that our disclosure controls and procedures were effective as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	May
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	at the reasonable assurance level.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:27PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 17.1PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Management&#x2019;s Report on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-INDENT:31.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	The following sets forth, in accordance with Section 404(a) of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 and Item 308 of the Securities and Exchange Commission&#x2019;s Regulation S-K, the report of management on our internal control over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-INDENT:40.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	1.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 33.9PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	Our management is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. &#x201C;Internal control over financial reporting&#x201D; is a process designed by, or under the supervision of, our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, together with other financial officers, and effected by our Board of Directors, management and other personnel, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles and includes those policies and procedures that:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 21.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:11PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;WIDTH:15PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Pertain to the maintenance of records that in reasonable detail accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of our assets;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 21.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:11PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;WIDTH:15PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that our receipts and expenditures are being made only in accordance with authorizations of our management and directors; and
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 21.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:11PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:15PT;WIDTH:15PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use or disposition of our assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-INDENT:40.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	2.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 33.9PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Our management, in accordance with Rule 13a-15(c) under the Exchange Act and with the participation of our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, together with other financial officers, evaluated the effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	May 28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The framework on which management&#x2019;s evaluation of our internal control over financial reporting is based is the &#x201C;Internal Control &#x2013; Integrated Framework&#x201D;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	published in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	2013
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations (&#x201C;COSO&#x201D;) of the Treadway Commission.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-INDENT:40.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	3.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 33.9PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	Management has determined that our internal control over financial reporting as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	May 28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	is effective. It is noted that internal control over financial reporting cannot provide absolute assurance of achieving financial reporting objectives, but rather reasonable assurance of achieving such objectives.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:90%;TEXT-INDENT:40.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	4.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 33.9PT 0PT 0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	The attestation report of FROST, PLLC on our internal control over financial reporting, which includes that firm&#x2019;s opinion on the effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting, is set forth below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 11PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
	(b)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;;FONT-SIZE: 11PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;PADDING:0PT 17.1PT 0PT 0PT;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:11PT;COLOR:#000000;">
